250
00:15:24.004 --> 00:15:26.444
It has to be placed anyways. It's standard of care.

251
00:15:26.524 --> 00:15:30.244
It relieves the fluid that otherwise accumulates after

252
00:15:30.304 --> 00:15:30.744
surgery.

253
00:15:31.664 --> 00:15:33.564
It was previously just thrown in the garbage.

254
00:15:34.304 --> 00:15:38.264
So we use it as a practical source of biomarkers for MRD.

255
00:15:38.464 --> 00:15:42.184
We published on this in the HPV positive setting, and then more recently,

256
00:15:42.194 --> 00:15:46.154
January of this year in the HPV negative head and neck cancer setting.

257
00:15:47.184 --> 00:15:49.894
So what we did is we did tumor-informed

258
00:15:52.284 --> 00:15:55.754
next generation sequencing, focusing on single nucleotide variants,

259
00:15:56.304 --> 00:15:59.784
using a panel that targets 700 mutations that

260
00:15:59.884 --> 00:16:01.964
are specific to head and neck cancer.

261
00:16:02.644 --> 00:16:06.524
And we applied this error-corrected tumor-informed approach to both

262
00:16:06.544 --> 00:16:10.304
plasma as well as lymphatic fluid 24 hours

263
00:16:10.384 --> 00:16:11.044
after surgery.

264
00:16:12.524 --> 00:16:15.404
And what we found was that initially, 24 hours

265
00:16:15.444 --> 00:16:18.814
postoperatively, the serosanguinous fluid in the surgical

266
00:16:18.904 --> 00:16:21.174
drain is characteristic of lymph.

267
00:16:21.704 --> 00:16:23.684
It's enriched in lymph-associated proteins.

268
00:16:24.044 --> 00:16:27.984
Also, the cell-free DNA yields are much higher than plasma, and the mean

269
00:16:28.084 --> 00:16:30.564
AFs are also much higher than plasma.

270
00:16:30.684 --> 00:16:33.984
So you really have enrichment of both cfDNA and

271
00:16:34.044 --> 00:16:36.804
ctDNA in this lymphatic fluid compared to plasma.

272
00:16:38.064 --> 00:16:41.954
Lymph ctDNA MRD was associated with worse PFS, so when

273
00:16:41.984 --> 00:16:45.804
we looked 24 hours after surgery, that was associated with worse progression-free

274
00:16:45.904 --> 00:16:49.394
survival, as well as, importantly, worse local regional

275
00:16:49.404 --> 00:16:53.324
progression-free survival. So now we are getting local regional insight

276
00:16:53.334 --> 00:16:55.584
that previously was unavailable to us.

277
00:16:56.524 --> 00:17:00.224
Lymph ctDNA importantly outperformed individual pathology

278
00:17:00.264 --> 00:17:04.024
features, the features that our colleagues use to

279
00:17:04.085 --> 00:17:07.774
inform them to give adjuvant radiation or adjuvant chemo

280
00:17:07.844 --> 00:17:08.164
RT.

281
00:17:09.364 --> 00:17:11.464
We're able to outperform them with lymph ctDNA.

282
00:17:11.565 --> 00:17:15.424
We outperform external extension, perineural invasion, nodal stage,

283
00:17:15.504 --> 00:17:16.785
and lymphovascular invasion.

284
00:17:18.585 --> 00:17:22.184
And lymph ctDNA MRD remained prognostic in patients with low or

285
00:17:22.364 --> 00:17:24.154
intermediate risk pathology features.

286
00:17:24.664 --> 00:17:28.204
Here in patients with N0, we were able to identify certain patients who

287
00:17:28.264 --> 00:17:31.744
otherwise wouldn't be offered radiation, but who still have

288
00:17:32.304 --> 00:17:35.504
poor survival outcomes, who might have benefited from adjuvant RT.

289
00:17:36.104 --> 00:17:40.004
And then patients who are node positive but ENE negative, who otherwise wouldn't

290
00:17:40.024 --> 00:17:43.704
be given chemoradiation, but might have benefited because they're doing

291
00:17:43.784 --> 00:17:45.624
quite poor with radiation alone.

292
00:17:46.924 --> 00:17:50.244
And importantly, lymph ctDNA 24 hours significantly

293
00:17:50.384 --> 00:17:54.084
stratified progression-free survival, while plasma did not at this

294
00:17:54.204 --> 00:17:55.064
early time point.

295
00:17:56.324 --> 00:18:00.264
I'm now going to pivot and talk about another exciting project in our lab, and this

296
00:18:00.304 --> 00:18:03.784
is immunotherapy. And I'll give kind of an overview of where we

297
00:18:03.864 --> 00:18:06.374
started with immunotherapy response prediction and

298
00:18:07.404 --> 00:18:09.604
how I started with some of my visioning for this project.

299
00:18:09.644 --> 00:18:13.604
So I've been really intrigued by tumor mutational burden, which has been

300
00:18:13.664 --> 00:18:16.064
shown to be a biomarker for immunotherapy response.

301
00:18:18.144 --> 00:18:21.024
And in our earlier work, we showed that we can infer

302
00:18:22.604 --> 00:18:26.264
TMB from plasma cell-free DNA from the targeted hybrid

303
00:18:26.324 --> 00:18:28.644
capture panel itself, which makes sense.

304
00:18:29.104 --> 00:18:32.604
The panel is a-... subset of the exome.

305
00:18:32.834 --> 00:18:36.254
So just with simple linear regression, you can infer what's in the whole

306
00:18:36.334 --> 00:18:39.594
exome by interpolating from what's in the subset of it.

307
00:18:40.954 --> 00:18:44.614
We did something similar from urine too, to infer TMB from urine cell-free

308
00:18:44.654 --> 00:18:44.954
DNA.

309
00:18:45.914 --> 00:18:47.734
And then our colleagues at Foundation

310
00:18:49.974 --> 00:18:53.944
Medicine, they showed that blood-based TMB can predict progression-free

311
00:18:54.014 --> 00:18:57.914
survival on immunotherapy, and then they tried to validate this in a

312
00:18:57.954 --> 00:19:01.654
prospective study, but this study was negative.

313
00:19:01.754 --> 00:19:05.594
Yes, TMB is working, but it may or may

314
00:19:05.634 --> 00:19:09.434
not really be working. This is a negative study, very compelling, really

315
00:19:09.494 --> 00:19:10.914
beautiful nature medicine paper.

316
00:19:11.304 --> 00:19:14.914
But are we really moving the needle in terms of being able to predict IO

317
00:19:14.954 --> 00:19:18.934
response with TMB or with the

318
00:19:19.054 --> 00:19:21.174
liquid surrogate blood TMB? I'm not sure.

319
00:19:21.864 --> 00:19:25.514
And so we wondered, can we profile the tumor microenvironment from liquid

320
00:19:25.594 --> 00:19:29.494
biopsy to predict IO response? And this is work with my

321
00:19:29.514 --> 00:19:33.244
dear friend and colleague, Erin Newman at Stanford, brilliant computational

322
00:19:33.334 --> 00:19:34.014
biologist.

323
00:19:34.974 --> 00:19:38.894
We put together a study to try to do liquid

324
00:19:38.914 --> 00:19:42.574
biopsy of the tumor microenvironment, and we did this very rigorously.

325
00:19:42.614 --> 00:19:46.314
We started by doing spatial transcriptomics on 100

326
00:19:46.354 --> 00:19:49.504
tumors across 10 cancer types in four spatial transcriptomic

327
00:19:49.554 --> 00:19:53.174
modalities. We learned that there are these co-associated cell

328
00:19:53.274 --> 00:19:56.894
states in the tumor microenvironment that are very stereotypical,

329
00:19:57.914 --> 00:19:58.574
such that

330
00:20:00.274 --> 00:20:03.834
different patients with different cancer types, those cancers cluster

331
00:20:03.874 --> 00:20:07.034
better based on the spatial ecotypes in terms of their

332
00:20:07.054 --> 00:20:10.914
prognosis compared to within the cancer types themselves.

333
00:20:11.974 --> 00:20:15.634
We developed a Google Maps of sorts of where these spatial

334
00:20:15.734 --> 00:20:18.134
ecotypes live within the tumor microenvironment.

335
00:20:18.474 --> 00:20:22.114
They showed that they have prognostic as well as predictive significance, and then

336
00:20:22.154 --> 00:20:25.894
we translated that to plasma cell-free DNA methylation

337
00:20:25.974 --> 00:20:29.734
using an advanced binary neural network model, and we showed that we could use

338
00:20:29.834 --> 00:20:32.074
that to predict immunotherapy response.

339
00:20:33.414 --> 00:20:37.354
So I'm showing you this because for a long time this has been a

340
00:20:37.454 --> 00:20:41.094
pet peeve of mine. We, including me, have been using this word liquid

341
00:20:41.174 --> 00:20:43.894
biopsy, but is that really accurate?

342
00:20:44.994 --> 00:20:48.714
With liquid biopsy technologies, with ctDNA, we're only looking at malignant

343
00:20:48.754 --> 00:20:52.384
cells. When a pathologist looks under the microscope, they're seeing much

344
00:20:52.414 --> 00:20:56.214
more. There are all these microenvironmental cells that have been invisible to

345
00:20:56.334 --> 00:20:57.974
us in the liquid domain.

346
00:20:59.054 --> 00:20:59.174
So

347
00:21:00.054 --> 00:21:02.364
it felt like something that we had to address.

348
00:21:03.494 --> 00:21:07.474
How can we really capture a greater portion of liquid

349
00:21:07.494 --> 00:21:11.314
biopsy from plasma to go beyond just the tumor cells?

350
00:21:13.194 --> 00:21:15.714
So we started by doing spatial transcriptomics and

351
00:21:16.694 --> 00:21:20.454
very simply, you divide up the tumor microenvironment into an inner

352
00:21:20.494 --> 00:21:24.274
margin that's sitting right next to the tumor cells, an outer margin that's sitting

353
00:21:24.334 --> 00:21:26.264
outside of that, and then the outer stroma.

354
00:21:26.334 --> 00:21:30.244
I'm showing an example here of melanoma with Merscope and then

355
00:21:30.254 --> 00:21:31.854
breast cancer with 10x Visium.

356
00:21:33.974 --> 00:21:36.574
And then what we saw was interestingly, we see

357
00:21:37.954 --> 00:21:41.614
that these spatially defined cell states form a continuum

358
00:21:41.674 --> 00:21:45.614
reflecting the physical distance between the tumor and the

359
00:21:45.694 --> 00:21:49.594
outer stroma. So we're seeing really a shift in the tumor immune cell

360
00:21:49.694 --> 00:21:53.594
states and stromal cell states as you go from right next to the tumor out to the

361
00:21:53.634 --> 00:21:56.524
outer stroma. And not only that, we see that these

362
00:21:57.094 --> 00:22:01.014
spatially conserved neighborhoods of cell states, they also

363
00:22:01.054 --> 00:22:04.584
shift as you're going from the inner core out to the outer edges of the

364
00:22:04.654 --> 00:22:05.153
galaxy.

365
00:22:06.574 --> 00:22:09.914
These spatial ecotypes, as I was saying, they have distinct geographic

366
00:22:09.974 --> 00:22:10.834
localization,

367
00:22:12.134 --> 00:22:15.614
and they consist of spatially co-localized cell states.

368
00:22:16.434 --> 00:22:17.214
And interestingly,

369
00:22:18.774 --> 00:22:20.714
spatial ecotype one has fibroblasts.

370
00:22:21.534 --> 00:22:25.474
Spatial ecotype three has fibroblasts. Spatial ecotype four has fibroblasts.

371
00:22:26.014 --> 00:22:29.974
Five, six, seven, and eight. But these are different fibroblast cell states.

372
00:22:30.534 --> 00:22:34.234
The cell states that are living right next to the core are different than the ones

373
00:22:34.254 --> 00:22:37.634
that are living right outside, all the way outside in the outer edges of the

374
00:22:37.714 --> 00:22:38.034
stroma.

375
00:22:39.414 --> 00:22:39.674
So

376
00:22:40.794 --> 00:22:43.534
we're seeing here these co-localized cell states,

377
00:22:44.514 --> 00:22:47.653
and we're seeing them from spatial transcriptomics data.

378
00:22:47.734 --> 00:22:51.394
I'm going to focus here on spatial ecotype seven and four, which I'm going to show

379
00:22:51.454 --> 00:22:54.214
later are associated with IO response versus resistance.

380
00:22:54.734 --> 00:22:58.594
Spatial ecotype seven is sitting right there, right within the tumor

381
00:22:58.614 --> 00:23:02.294
cells, right in that inner margin area, while spatial ecotype

382
00:23:02.354 --> 00:23:04.774
four is hanging out there in the outer stroma.

383
00:23:06.474 --> 00:23:06.934
We then,

384
00:23:08.094 --> 00:23:11.074
for practical reasons, we developed Spatial Ecotyper to

385
00:23:11.174 --> 00:23:15.034
quantify spatial cellular ecosystems from bulk RNA-seq

386
00:23:15.074 --> 00:23:19.054
data. I'm showing here that it's faithful to the ground

387
00:23:19.114 --> 00:23:22.954
truth spatial transcriptomics. So we can now deconvolve these

388
00:23:23.034 --> 00:23:26.854
spatial ecotypes from bulk RNA-seq, and this now lets us

389
00:23:26.974 --> 00:23:30.654
analyze across TCGA, analyze across 17 carcinoma

390
00:23:30.674 --> 00:23:32.894
types and melanoma across TCGA,

391
00:23:34.234 --> 00:23:37.974
and then importantly, also access these IO studies.

392
00:23:38.254 --> 00:23:41.994
So these are 15 different studies of immunotherapy across four

393
00:23:42.014 --> 00:23:45.794
different cancer types with pretreatment tumor tissue that

394
00:23:45.954 --> 00:23:49.594
RNA-seq was run on. So we're able to secondarily analyze that with

395
00:23:49.694 --> 00:23:53.534
Spatial Ecotyper, and when we do that, we see that spatial ecotype

396
00:23:53.614 --> 00:23:57.514
seven and eight are strongly associated with immunotherapy response and

397
00:23:57.614 --> 00:24:01.414
outperform other biomarkers. While spatial ecotype four is strongly

398
00:24:01.424 --> 00:24:05.394
associated with immunotherapy resistance and outperforms other biomarkers.

399
00:24:06.694 --> 00:24:10.614
We then developed a binary neural network method in order

400
00:24:10.674 --> 00:24:14.574
to translate this to the liquid cell-free DNA methylome

401
00:24:14.614 --> 00:24:18.074
space in order to infer these spatial

402
00:24:18.214 --> 00:24:21.774
ecotypes from liquid biopsy cell-free DNA methylomes.

403
00:24:23.614 --> 00:24:27.334
Using this binary neural network model, I'm going to show you one of our

404
00:24:27.374 --> 00:24:31.314
validation data sets. There are multiple of these, and I invite you to look at

405
00:24:31.354 --> 00:24:33.414
our paper in "Nature" that's going to come out in two weeks.

406
00:24:33.954 --> 00:24:37.334
But here what we did is we did spatial transcriptomics on the tumor

407
00:24:37.374 --> 00:24:41.074
tissue as well as paired plasma, and you're seeing here an overall

408
00:24:41.084 --> 00:24:45.014
correlation between the ground truth tumor Visium data as

409
00:24:45.074 --> 00:24:48.914
well as the normalized rank spatial ecotype levels in plasma

410
00:24:49.014 --> 00:24:52.904
cell-free DNA methylomes.Spatial ecotype 7

411
00:24:52.944 --> 00:24:56.464
is associated with response. Spatial ecotype 4 is associated with resistance.

412
00:24:56.544 --> 00:25:00.084
So there's a yin-yang relationship there. Seven is high, four is low.

413
00:25:00.184 --> 00:25:04.064
Four is high, seven is low. We see that in plasma, we see that in ground

414
00:25:04.104 --> 00:25:07.944
true tumor tissue as well. So here we've developed for the first

415
00:25:07.964 --> 00:25:11.684
time ever a non-invasive platform for spatial biology.

416
00:25:13.224 --> 00:25:16.404
So we then move this into two validation sets.

417
00:25:16.444 --> 00:25:18.004
I'm showing one here. The other was

418
00:25:18.864 --> 00:25:20.944
in the poster that I presented on Sunday.

419
00:25:21.564 --> 00:25:24.444
So focusing here on 80 patients with melanoma

420
00:25:25.304 --> 00:25:29.104
with response that was scored, we measured that spatial

421
00:25:29.184 --> 00:25:33.144
ecotype 7, 8, and 4 showing those, and ctDNA.

422
00:25:33.524 --> 00:25:36.944
Seven and 8 are associated with response, 4 is associated with resistance.

423
00:25:37.304 --> 00:25:40.644
Ultrasensitive ctDNA is not associated with response or resistance.

424
00:25:41.324 --> 00:25:44.444
So 7 is associated with response as well as improved survival,

425
00:25:45.324 --> 00:25:48.504
4 is associated with resistance and worse survival.

426
00:25:48.544 --> 00:25:50.324
And this importantly is pre-treatment.

427
00:25:50.504 --> 00:25:54.294
So prior to IO, we're already able to measure

428
00:25:54.444 --> 00:25:57.784
non-invasively what is happening in the tumor microenvironment and

429
00:25:57.844 --> 00:26:01.694
portend survival outcomes. Again, spatial ecotype 7

430
00:26:02.184 --> 00:26:05.744
forecasted immunotherapy benefit and spatial ecotype 4

431
00:26:05.784 --> 00:26:08.184
forecasted immunotherapy resistance.

432
00:26:09.124 --> 00:26:12.744
And this held up on multivariate analysis while PD-L1 and

433
00:26:12.804 --> 00:26:16.694
TMB did not. And I'm showing here where we see the

434
00:26:16.824 --> 00:26:20.504
future going, where we can track these

435
00:26:20.604 --> 00:26:22.984
liquid spatial ecotypes serially,

436
00:26:24.684 --> 00:26:28.284
perhaps even in an MRD setting. And I'm showing here a

437
00:26:28.324 --> 00:26:32.304
patient who we thought had progressive disease, but turned out that they had

438
00:26:32.324 --> 00:26:36.204
pseudoprogression. And you see spatial ecotype 4 falling and

439
00:26:36.284 --> 00:26:40.064
spatial ecotype 7 rising, really portending this

440
00:26:40.124 --> 00:26:43.424
ultimate response over a year earlier

441
00:26:44.284 --> 00:26:47.884
than it actually happened, at a time point when we were totally vexed because we

442
00:26:47.924 --> 00:26:50.564
thought they had progression, but they actually had pseudoprogression.

443
00:26:51.904 --> 00:26:54.384
Recently, we've extended this to non-small cell lung cancer.

444
00:26:54.424 --> 00:26:56.584
I'm just showing the pilot data here.

445
00:26:56.684 --> 00:26:58.164
So this is

446
00:26:59.183 --> 00:27:02.584
data showing that in lung cancer we also see that these spatial

447
00:27:02.664 --> 00:27:06.584
ecotypes associated with immunotherapy response versus resistance,

448
00:27:06.604 --> 00:27:10.064
and that in the liquid space we're able to predict immunotherapy response versus

449
00:27:10.104 --> 00:27:13.944
resistance, including in neoadjuvant therapy when PD-L1 and

450
00:27:14.004 --> 00:27:17.624
TMB are not able to perform. And I think this could give us incredible

451
00:27:17.704 --> 00:27:21.264
precision, especially in the neoadjuvant space where decision-making

452
00:27:21.344 --> 00:27:24.874
skills are really lacking because it's unclear should the patient get

453
00:27:24.884 --> 00:27:28.704
neoadjuvant and go to surgery, or should they come to me to get chemo RT?

454
00:27:29.484 --> 00:27:32.934
So in summary, liquid biopsy cell-free DNA analysis using

455
00:27:32.984 --> 00:27:36.524
ultrasensitive methods enables MRD detection and treatment response

456
00:27:36.544 --> 00:27:40.204
prediction. Sampling cell-free DNA local regionally from

457
00:27:40.304 --> 00:27:44.144
surgical lymphatic fluid in head and neck cancer can boost ctDNA

458
00:27:44.184 --> 00:27:47.104
detection sensitivity and risk stratify low and intermediate-risk patients.

459
00:27:47.644 --> 00:27:51.184
And cell-free DNA methylation analysis using spatial

460
00:27:51.224 --> 00:27:54.844
transcriptomics-derived AI enables liquid biopsy of the tumor

461
00:27:54.924 --> 00:27:58.374
microenvironment and prediction of immunotherapy response.

462
00:27:58.944 --> 00:28:02.934
So I'd like to thank my lab members, I'd like to thank my collaborators,

463
00:28:02.964 --> 00:28:06.924
and for this work, especially Aaron Newman at Stanford and Jose Zevallos

464
00:28:06.944 --> 00:28:10.264
at Pittsburgh, my funding sources, and most importantly, patients and their

465
00:28:10.304 --> 00:28:11.384
families. Thank you very much.

466
00:28:17.924 --> 00:28:19.704
You just have three minutes for questions.

467
00:28:19.784 --> 00:28:19.904
So

468
00:28:21.404 --> 00:28:25.284
if anyone has questions, please step up to the microphone, or you

469
00:28:25.304 --> 00:28:29.284
can submit your questions in the meeting app, or using the

470
00:28:29.404 --> 00:28:30.804
QR code here up on the slide.

471
00:28:32.364 --> 00:28:33.184
Hi, Chaudhry.

472
00:28:34.044 --> 00:28:36.764
Thank you for your talk. I'm from Mayo Clinic,

473
00:28:37.604 --> 00:28:40.664
earlier from Rochester, now in Jacksonville, Carty Therapeutics.

474
00:28:41.304 --> 00:28:42.764
My question is regarding

475
00:28:43.684 --> 00:28:47.304
how can these technologies help the Lynch syndrome patients?

476
00:28:47.864 --> 00:28:48.564
Because

477
00:28:49.824 --> 00:28:53.464
you cannot... This is about MRD, but even if you can talk

478
00:28:53.544 --> 00:28:57.484
about the early detection for small bowel cancers

479
00:28:57.544 --> 00:29:00.664
as well as urothelial cancers,

480
00:29:01.104 --> 00:29:03.804
uterine cancers in Lynch syndrome patients.

481
00:29:05.344 --> 00:29:06.724
No, it's a great question.

482
00:29:08.964 --> 00:29:10.333
There's a lot

483
00:29:11.184 --> 00:29:14.564
of exciting work happening in the early detection space.

484
00:29:15.544 --> 00:29:19.384
And there, I think some of the principles that make that unique compared to

485
00:29:19.464 --> 00:29:22.544
MRD is that we don't have tumor information.

486
00:29:23.004 --> 00:29:26.744
Someone is coming in, even if they have predisposing risks, we don't

487
00:29:26.824 --> 00:29:29.254
know what that tumor will look like.

488
00:29:29.284 --> 00:29:32.764
And so the field has moved away from

489
00:29:33.264 --> 00:29:37.254
mutation-based approaches and towards epigenomic approaches, such

490
00:29:37.254 --> 00:29:38.304
as using methylation.

491
00:29:39.504 --> 00:29:41.804
But would be happy to talk to you more about that.

492
00:29:44.304 --> 00:29:47.844
Thank you, Adil. Excellent talk, and also

493
00:29:47.904 --> 00:29:49.564
congratulations to your "Nature" paper.

494
