01:05:38.058 --> 01:05:41.838
Each MRD assay has a different upper bound on breadth and depth.

1104
01:05:42.858 --> 01:05:46.838
Each patient's tumor has a different tumor mutation burden

1105
01:05:46.878 --> 01:05:50.778
and subset of low noise mutations that permit ultrasensitive

1106
01:05:50.798 --> 01:05:54.058
detection. And in some patients, it's a very small subset.

1107
01:05:54.898 --> 01:05:58.168
And if you only have, let's say, 100

1108
01:05:58.938 --> 01:06:02.908
ultra-low noise mutations that are tracked in those 3,000 genomes, you only have

1109
01:06:03.098 --> 01:06:07.038
300,000 informative molecules tested for those ultra-low

1110
01:06:07.078 --> 01:06:09.788
noise mutations. You can't detect below one part per million.

1111
01:06:10.278 --> 01:06:13.688
Even though you technically have the sufficient error rate to get there, you don't

1112
01:06:13.718 --> 01:06:16.118
have enough molecules to reach that level of detection.

1113
01:06:17.898 --> 01:06:21.718
Each sample also has a varied cell-free DNA yield, and that constrains depth.

1114
01:06:22.438 --> 01:06:25.968
So basically, breadth times depth is inversely proportional to LoD95, and you can

1115
01:06:25.978 --> 01:06:28.408
predict LoD95 easily with a binomial model.

1116
01:06:29.518 --> 01:06:32.048
So the reality is LoD95s vary widely,

1117
01:06:33.258 --> 01:06:35.908
10x, maybe even 100x in real patient samples,

1118
01:06:36.978 --> 01:06:39.458
and contributes to the false negative problem.

